			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: New to EQ<a name="60455"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 4 04 6:50 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>EQ Guilds...
<br />

<br />
Every guild is different, really.  A lot depends on the level of the members etc.  I could generalize bigtime, and describe some different &quot;types&quot; of guilds, perhaps:
<br />

<br />
<u>Lowbee &quot;Shout&quot; Guild:</u>
<br />

<br />
I'm not sure how many there are of these left on many servers, since there are few real newbies on most.  But when I first started, and somewhat on FV server, there were always guilds that recruited by shouting in lowbie zones.  I'm not sure what it is like to be in one though.  These guilds tend to have a reputation for being amateurish and n00bish.  Some though develop into Family guilds or Raiding guilds eventually.
<br />

<br />
<u>&quot;Family Style&quot; Guild:</u>
<br />

<br />
I was in one of these, and Molto really would fall into this kind of category, though we are decidedly different from any guild in the game, being only bards.  A Family Guild is basically a bunch of friends who share a chat channel, and help each other out with things.  They usually help each other with the Epic quests, but often have a hard time organizing raids or raiding often enough to really &quot;progress&quot; through the content of the game.
<br />

<br />
Often, these guilds have a strong sense of companionship and loyalty, much like a family.  Often, the desire of some members to progress their character and/or obtain better gear etc. causes rifts in these otherwise harmonious guilds.  Those how leave to be &quot;uber&quot; are often villified as being somehow disloyal, while those who want more high-end action and raiding criticize the guild's leaders for being ineffective... 
<br />

<br />
This is NOT necessarily what happens with every Family guild.  Many will make the shift to &quot;Casual Raiding Guild&quot; and thus satisfy most people's desire for progress.  I have witnessed the demise of several &quot;Family Guilds&quot; though, and it is painful when it happens.
<br />

<br />
Many times, Family Guilds end up dividing and splintering as they grow, and members level up.  This is because some folks will want to raid more often and more intensely to progress through game content.  (Planes of Power flags... getting nicer gear etc.)  Sometimes they split up, or end up having people leave to be part of the next guild type...
<br />

<br />
<u>&quot;Uber&quot; Raiding Guild</u>
<br />

<br />
These guilds often have minimum level, gear, and AA requirements, and extensive application processes just to get in.  The are hard-core raiders, some with a required amount of raiding members must attend.  They are very serious about &quot;winning&quot; and moving up, and gearing up.  They often employ &quot;DKP&quot; (dragon kill points) for loot distribution.  That is, you get points for attending raids, and you use those points to bid for items that drop.  Though a bit inpersonal, it is a good system, and is the most &quot;fair&quot; way to distribute loots.
<br />

<br />
<u>&quot;Casual&quot; Raiding Guild</u>
<br />

<br />
Midway between the &quot;Family&quot; Guild and the ubers, the Casual raiding guild raids two to four nights a week.  Usually attendance is not required.  Some will use DKP, some will have &quot;Loot Councils&quot; and others straight &quot;NBG Random&quot; (need before greed, roll dice for winners of loot.  &quot;Need before greed&quot; means you don't roll on something that you will not use as an upgrade to your gear-- you aren't just going to sell it.)
<br />

<br />
<u>Roleplay Guilds:</u>
<br />

<br />
On Firiona Vie server especially, you will find guilds that are devoted to Roleplay.  They stay in character in the guild channel.  The create story lines for their characters that intereact with one another.  Often, they will have some theme, or will be Good-only, or Evil-only etc.  These guilds are increasingly rare to find, even on FV, the &quot;Roleplay preferred&quot; server.
<br />

<br />
<u>Conclusion:</u>
<br />

<br />
At the core, a Guild is a bunch of friends who help each other out in the game.  Whether that means just facilitating grouping together, and perhaps raiding for epic quest hits, or whether that means a disciplined, focused organization bent on &quot;beating&quot; the game and being the &quot;best of the best,&quot; or something in between the two.  Most EQ players will eventually join a guild.  Some will stick loyally to one, while others might bounce around a bit, trying to find that perfect fit.  In the end, it's a way to enhance the fun you have playing the game, by having a group of friends committed to playing it with you.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=564823">Scherzo Glissando </a><BR>
Maestro, Molto Espressivo</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
